---
import ToolLayout from '../../layouts/ToolLayout.astro';

const SITE = 'https://healthcalculation.com';
const canonical = `${SITE}/guides/how-to-use-one-rep-max`;

const schemaArticle = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Article',
  headline: 'How to Use Your One Rep Max to Build Strength',
  description: 'What your 1RM means, how to calculate training weights by percentage, and how to program strength, hypertrophy, and endurance using rep max zones.',
  url: canonical,
  datePublished: '2025-06-01',
  dateModified: '2025-06-18',
  author: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'HealthCalculation.com' },
  publisher: { '@type': 'Organization', name: 'HealthCalculation.com', url: SITE },
};

const schemaFaq = [
  {
    q: 'What is a one rep max (1RM)?',
    a: 'A one rep max (1RM) is the maximum weight you can lift for exactly one complete repetition with proper form on a given exercise. It is the standard measure of absolute strength in powerlifting, weightlifting, and strength training. Your 1RM is used to calculate training loads as percentages — for example, training at 75% of 1RM for sets of 8 reps.',
  },
  {
    q: 'What is a good one rep max for bench press, squat, and deadlift?',
    a: 'Strength standards vary by body weight and training experience. For untrained adult men, a reasonable benchmark is a bench press 1RM equal to body weight, squat 1RM at 1.25x body weight, and deadlift 1RM at 1.5x body weight. For intermediate lifters (2+ years): bench 1.25x, squat 1.75x, deadlift 2.0x body weight. Elite powerlifters often exceed 2x body weight on bench and 3x on squat and deadlift.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Which 1RM formula is most accurate?',
    a: 'Research shows the Epley and Brzycki formulas are the most accurate across most rep ranges. Epley (1RM = weight x (1 + reps/30)) is the most widely used. Brzycki performs better at lower rep counts (1-5 reps). The Lander formula was designed specifically for the bench press. All formulas become less accurate above 10 reps — for best results, use submaximal sets of 3-5 reps to estimate your 1RM.',
  },
  {
    q: 'How do I train using percentages of my 1RM?',
    a: 'Different percentage ranges target different training adaptations: 90-100% of 1RM (1-3 reps) develops maximum strength. 75-85% (6-10 reps) is the hypertrophy zone for muscle size. 60-75% (12-20 reps) builds muscular endurance. A standard strength program might use 3-5 sets at 80-85% 1RM three times per week on main lifts, cycling intensity over a 4-week block.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Is it safe to test your actual one rep max?',
    a: 'Testing your true 1RM carries injury risk, particularly for beginners. A safer approach for most people is to use a submaximal test: lift a challenging weight for 3-5 reps with good form, then plug the numbers into a 1RM formula. This gives a reliable estimate without maximal loading. If you do test a true 1RM, always use spotters, warm up thoroughly, and avoid failure on your first attempt.',
  },
];
---

