<article class="guide-article">

<nav class="breadcrumb" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
  <a href="/">Home</a><span>&#8250;</span><a href="/guides">Guides</a><span>&#8250;</span><span>One Rep Max Guide</span>
</nav>

<p class="guide-intro">Your one rep max (1RM) is more than a bragging right — it is the foundation of intelligent strength programming. Once you know your 1RM, you can calculate the exact weight to use for any set and rep target, track long-term progress objectively, and structure periodization blocks that keep you improving.</p>

<h2>The 4 Most Used 1RM Estimation Formulas</h2>
<p>You do not need to test your true 1RM to use it. Lift a challenging weight for 3–10 reps, then plug the numbers into any of these formulas:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Formula</th><th>Equation</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td><strong>Epley</strong> (1985)</td><td>1RM = w × (1 + r ÷ 30)</td><td>General use — most widely cited</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Brzycki</strong> (1993)</td><td>1RM = w ÷ (1.0278 − 0.0278 × r)</td><td>More accurate at low rep counts (1–5)</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lander</strong> (1985)</td><td>1RM = 100w ÷ (101.3 − 2.67 × r)</td><td>Designed for bench press</td></tr>
    <tr><td><strong>Lombardi</strong> (1989)</td><td>1RM = w × r^0.10</td><td>Higher rep ranges (8–12)</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>
<p style="font-size:13px;color:#6b7280;margin-top:8px">w = weight lifted, r = number of reps completed. Average all four for the most robust estimate.</p>

<h2>Training Percentage Zones</h2>
<p>Once you have your 1RM, use these percentages to calculate the right weight for each training goal:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Zone</th><th>% of 1RM</th><th>Reps per Set</th><th>Primary Adaptation</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Max Strength</td><td>93–100%</td><td>1–2</td><td>Neural efficiency, absolute strength</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Strength</td><td>85–92%</td><td>2–4</td><td>Strength with some hypertrophy</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Strength-Size</td><td>77–84%</td><td>5–8</td><td>Balanced strength and muscle growth</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Hypertrophy</td><td>67–76%</td><td>8–12</td><td>Muscle size (primary hypertrophy zone)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Endurance</td><td>50–66%</td><td>15–25</td><td>Muscular endurance, metabolic conditioning</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Example: Training Weights from a 100 kg 1RM</h2>
<p>If your squat 1RM is 100 kg, here are your training weights across the zones:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Goal</th><th>% 1RM</th><th>Weight (kg)</th><th>Target Reps</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Peaking / max effort</td><td>95%</td><td>95 kg</td><td>1–2</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Heavy strength work</td><td>87%</td><td>87 kg</td><td>3–4</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Main strength block</td><td>80%</td><td>80 kg</td><td>5–6</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Hypertrophy block</td><td>72%</td><td>72 kg</td><td>8–10</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Volume / deload</td><td>60%</td><td>60 kg</td><td>15–20</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Strength Standards by Body Weight</h2>
<p>How does your 1RM compare? These are commonly used relative strength benchmarks (1RM as a multiple of body weight) from strength and conditioning research:</p>

<table class="data-table">
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Level</th><th>Bench Press</th><th>Squat</th><th>Deadlift</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Beginner (men)</td><td>0.5× BW</td><td>0.75× BW</td><td>1.0× BW</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Novice (men)</td><td>0.75× BW</td><td>1.25× BW</td><td>1.5× BW</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Intermediate (men)</td><td>1.25× BW</td><td>1.75× BW</td><td>2.0× BW</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Advanced (men)</td><td>1.5× BW</td><td>2.25× BW</td><td>2.5× BW</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Beginner (women)</td><td>0.35× BW</td><td>0.5× BW</td><td>0.75× BW</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Intermediate (women)</td><td>0.75× BW</td><td>1.25× BW</td><td>1.5× BW</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Advanced (women)</td><td>1.0× BW</td><td>1.75× BW</td><td>2.0× BW</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>How to Progress Your 1RM Over Time</h2>
<p>Linear progression works well for beginners: add 2.5 kg per session on upper body lifts and 5 kg on lower body. Once progress stalls, switch to weekly or block periodization — cycle intensity across 3–4 week blocks (accumulation, intensification, realization/peak). Track your estimated 1RM monthly using a consistent submaximal test protocol to measure long-term progress without the injury risk of true max testing.</p>

